#: ../../G/Get-a-life-.rst:5
msgid "Get a life!"
msgstr "Get a life!"

#: ../../G/Get-a-life-.rst:7
msgid "imp\\."
msgstr "命令法"

#: ../../G/Get-a-life-.rst:9
msgid ""
"Hacker-standard way of suggesting that the person to whom it is directed has"
" succumbed to terminal geekdom (see :ref:`geek`\\). Often heard on "
":ref:`Usenet`\\, esp. as a way of suggesting that the target is taking some "
"obscure issue of :ref:`theology` too seriously. This exhortation was "
"popularized by William Shatner on a 1987 *Saturday Night Live* episode in a "
"speech that ended \"Get a life! \", but it can be traced back at least to "
"‘Valley Girl’ slang in 1983. It was certainly in wide use among hackers for "
"years before achieving mainstream currency via the sitcom *Get A Life* in "
"1990."
msgstr ""
"向けられた相手が末期的なギーク状態(\\ :ref:`geek`\\ を参照)に陥っていることを示唆する、ハッカー標準のやり方。\\ "
":ref:`Usenet`\\ でよく耳にし、特に相手がある難解な\\ :ref:`theology`\\ "
"の問題を真剣に受け止めすぎていることを示唆する方法として使われる。この激励は1987年の *Saturday Night Live* "
"のエピソードでWilliam Shatnerが「Get a life!」で終わるスピーチをしたことで広まったが、少なくとも1983年の‘Valley "
"Girl’スラングまでさかのぼることができる。1990年にシットコム *Get A Life* "
"を通じて主流の通用語になる何年も前から、ハッカーの間では確かに広く使われていた。"
